<doc id="153099" wikidata="Q5161151" url="?curid=153099" title="Normal closure (group theory)">
<text>In group theory, the normal closure of a subset formula_1 of a group formula_2 is the smallest normal subgroup of formula_2 containing formula_4

== Properties and description ==

Formally, if formula_2 is a group and formula_1 is a subset of formula_7 the normal closure formula_8 of formula_1 is the intersection of all normal subgroups of formula_2 containing formula_1:
formula_12

The normal closure formula_8 is the smallest normal subgroup of formula_2 containing formula_15 in the sense that formula_8 is a subset of every normal subgroup of formula_2 that contains formula_4

The subgroup formula_8 is generated by the set formula_20 of all conjugates of elements of formula_1 in formula_22

Therefore one can also write
formula_23

Any normal subgroup is equal to its normal closure. The conjugate closure of the empty set formula_24 is the trivial subgroup.

A variety of other notations are used for the normal closure in the literature, including formula_25 formula_26 formula_27 and formula_28

Dual to the concept of normal closure is that of or , defined as the join of all normal subgroups contained in formula_4

== Group presentations ==

For a group formula_2 given by a presentation formula_31 with generators formula_1 and defining relators formula_33 the presentation notation means that formula_2 is the quotient group formula_35 where formula_36 is a free group on formula_4

