<doc id="153130" wikidata="Q1335680" url="?curid=153130" title="Quaternion group">
<text>In group theory, the quaternion group Q8 (sometimes just denoted by Q) is a non-abelian group of order eight, isomorphic to the eight-element subset
formula_1 of the quaternions under multiplication. It is given by the group presentation

:formula_2

where &quot;e&quot; is the identity element and commutes with the other elements of the group. These relations, discovered by W. R. Hamilton, also generate the quaternions as an algebra over the real numbers.

Another presentation of Q8 is
:formula_3

Like many other finite groups, it can be realized as the Galois group of a certain field of algebraic numbers. 

== Compared to dihedral group ==

The quaternion group Q8 has the same order as the dihedral group D4, but a different structure, as shown by their Cayley and cycle graphs:

In the diagrams for D4, the group elements are marked with their action on a letter F in the defining representation R2. The same cannot be done for Q8, since it has no faithful representation in R2 or R3. D4 can be realized as a subset of the split-quaternions in the same way that Q8 can be viewed as a subset of the quaternions.

== Cayley table ==

The Cayley table (multiplication table) for Q8 is given by:

== Properties ==

The elements &quot;i&quot;, &quot;j&quot;, and &quot;k&quot; all have order four in Q8 and any two of them generate the entire group. Another presentation of Q8 based in only two elements to skip this redundancy is:

:formula_4

For instance, writing the group elements in lexicographically minimal normal forms, one may identify: formula_5 The quaternion group has the unusual property of being Hamiltonian: Q8 is non-abelian, but every subgroup is normal. Every Hamiltonian group contains a copy of Q8.

The quaternion group Q8 and the dihedral group D4 are the two smallest examples of a nilpotent non-abelian group.

The center and the commutator subgroup of Q8 is the subgroup formula_6. The inner automorphism group of Q8 is given by the group modulo its center, i.e. the factor group formula_7 which is isomorphic to the Klein four-group V. The full automorphism group of Q8 is isomorphic to S4, the symmetric group on four letters (see &quot;Matrix representations&quot; below), and the outer automorphism group of Q8 is thus S4/V, which is isomorphic to S3.

The quaternion group Q8 has five conjugacy classes, formula_8 and so five irreducible representations over the complex numbers, with dimensions 1, 1, 1, 1, 2:

Trivial representation.

Sign representations with i, j, k-kernel: Q8 has three maximal normal subgroups: the cyclic subgroups generated by i, j, and k respectively. For each maximal normal subgroup &quot;N&quot;, we obtain a one-dimensional representation factoring through the 2-element quotient group &quot;G&quot;/&quot;N&quot;. The representation sends elements of &quot;N&quot; to 1, and elements outside &quot;N&quot; to −1.

2-dimensional representation: Described below in &quot;Matrix representations&quot;. It is not realizable over the real numbers, but is a complex representation: indeed, it is just the quaternions formula_9 considered as an algebra over formula_10, and the action is that of left multiplication by formula_11.

The character table of Q8 turns out to be the same as that of D4: 
Nevertheless, all the irreducible characters formula_12 in the rows above have real values, this gives the decomposition of the real group algebra of formula_13 into minimal two-sided ideals:

:formula_14

where the idempotents formula_15 correspond to the irreducibles:

:formula_16

so that

:formula_17

Each of these irreducible ideals is isomorphic to a real central simple algebra, the first four to the real field formula_18. The last ideal formula_19 is isomorphic to the skew field of quaternions formula_9 by the correspondence:

:formula_21

Furthermore, the projection homomorphism formula_22 given by formula_23 has kernel ideal generated by the idempotent:

:formula_24

so the quaternions can also be obtained as the quotient ring formula_25. Note that this is irreducible as a real representation of formula_26, but splits into two copies of the two-dimensional irreducible when extended to the complex numbers. Indeed, the complex group algebra is formula_27 where formula_28 is the algebra of biquaternions.

== Matrix representations ==

The two-dimensional irreducible complex representation described above gives the quaternion group Q8 as a subgroup of the general linear group formula_29. The quaternion group is a multiplicative subgroup of the quaternion algebra:

:formula_30

which has a regular representation formula_31 by left multiplication on itself considered as a complex vector space with basis formula_32 so that formula_33 corresponds to the formula_34-linear mapping formula_35 The resulting representation

:formula_36

is given by:

:formula_37

Since all of the above matrices have unit determinant, this is a representation of Q8 in the special linear group formula_38.

A variant gives a representation by unitary matrices (table at right). Let formula_39 correspond to the linear mapping formula_40 so that formula_41 is given by:

:formula_42

It is worth noting that physicists exclusively use a different convention for the formula_43 matrix representation to make contact with the usual Pauli matrices:

:formula_44

This particular choice is convenient and elegant when one describes spin-1/2 states in the formula_45 basis and considers angular momentum ladder operators formula_46

There is also an important action of Q8 on the 2-dimensional vector space over the finite field formula_47 (table at right). A modular representation formula_48 is given by

:formula_49

This representation can be obtained from the extension field:

:formula_50

where formula_51 and the multiplicative group formula_52 has four generators, formula_53 of order 8. For each formula_54 the two-dimensional formula_55-vector space formula_56 admits a linear mapping:

:formula_57

In addition we have the Frobenius automorphism formula_58 satisfying formula_59 and formula_60 Then the above representation matrices are:

:formula_61

This representation realizes Q8 as a normal subgroup of . Thus, for each matrix formula_62, we have a group automorphism

:formula_63

with formula_64 In fact, these give the full automorphism group as:

:formula_65

This is isomorphic to the symmetric group S4 since the linear mappings formula_66 permute the four one-dimensional subspaces of formula_67 i.e., the four points of the projective space formula_68

Also, this representation permutes the eight non-zero vectors of formula_67 giving an embedding of Q8 in the symmetric group S8, in addition to the embeddings given by the regular representations.

==Galois group==
Richard Dedekind considered the field formula_70 in attempting to relate the quaternion group to Galois theory. In 1936 Ernst Witt published his approach to the quaternion group through Galois theory.

In 1981, Richard Dean showed the quaternion group can be realized as the Galois group Gal(T/Q) where Q is the field of rational numbers and T is the splitting field of the polynomial
:formula_71.
The development uses the fundamental theorem of Galois theory in specifying four intermediate fields between Q and T and their Galois groups, as well as two theorems on cyclic extension of degree four over a field.

==Generalized quaternion group==
A generalized quaternion group Q4&quot;n&quot; of order 4&quot;n&quot; is defined by the presentation
:formula_72
for an integer , with the usual quaternion group given by &quot;n&quot; = 2. Coxeter calls Q4&quot;n&quot; the dicyclic group formula_73, a special case of the binary polyhedral group formula_74 and related to the polyhedral group formula_75 and the dihedral group formula_76. The generalized quaternion group can be realized as the subgroup of formula_77 generated by

:formula_78

where formula_79. It can also be realized as the subgroup of unit quaternions generated by formula_80 and formula_81.

The generalized quaternion groups have the property that every abelian subgroup is cyclic. It can be shown that a finite &quot;p&quot;-group with this property (every abelian subgroup is cyclic) is either cyclic or a generalized quaternion group as defined above. Another characterization is that a finite &quot;p&quot;-group in which there is a unique subgroup of order &quot;p&quot; is either cyclic or a 2-group isomorphic to generalized quaternion group. In particular, for a finite field &quot;F&quot; with odd characteristic, the 2-Sylow subgroup of SL2(&quot;F&quot;) is non-abelian and has only one subgroup of order 2, so this 2-Sylow subgroup must be a generalized quaternion group, . Letting &quot;pr&quot; be the size of &quot;F&quot;, where &quot;p&quot; is prime, the size of the 2-Sylow subgroup of SL2(&quot;F&quot;) is 2&quot;n&quot;, where .

The Brauer–Suzuki theorem shows that the groups whose Sylow 2-subgroups are generalized quaternion cannot be simple.

Another terminology reserves the name &quot;generalized quaternion group&quot; for a dicyclic group of order a power of 2, which admits the presentation
:formula_82
